  "doc_id": "34560",
  "text": "T -helper 17 (Th17) cells, a subset of T-helper (CD4 þ ) cells, mainly produce interleukin (IL)-17, IL-17F, IL-21 and IL-22. IL-6-, IL-21-or IL-23-induced STAT3 (signal transducer and activator of transcription 3) activation facilitates Th17 differentiation [CITATION_1] 2 . IL-6 stimulation induces IL-21 production and an IL-21 self-amplifying loop; IL-23 further helps expansion and stabilization of Th17 population [CITATION_2] 2 . Conversely, the transforming growth factor-b (TGF-b)-Smad pathway limits Th1 and Th2 differentiation through downregulation of T-bet/GATA-3 expression, leading to increased Th17 differentiation. The recruitment of Th17 cells to different tissues is mediated by CCL20 and CCL22, along with their respective cognate chemokine receptors CCR6 and CCR4 (refs 3,4) . The proinflammatory cytokines IL-17 and IL-22 secreted by infiltrating Th17 cells can cause tissue damages 2 . Th17 cells are involved in many autoimmune diseases or inflammatory diseases, such as systemic lupus erythematosus, rheumatoid arthritis, multiple sclerosis, asthma, inflammatory bowel disease and type 2 diabetes (T2D) [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
